2. Using Tree, Multidimensional Scaling, and Kamada-Kawai layouts separately, what do you observe when you visualize your network ? Describe your observations for each of these layouts. Use at most 25 words for each layout. Include your observations in your written report, but not your code or its output.

- Plot using tree layout

  • The Tree shows an interesting character hierarchy, which makes sense, as Star Wars follows the Skywalker family through generations. The network combined the interactions of Anakin Skywalker and Darth Vader into one Darth Vader node, making its outdegree significantly higher than nodes.

- Plot using Multidimensional Scaling layout

  • The mdslayout produced a visually appealing graph, but there is a large cluster of nodes in one region, making it difficult to extract information from the visualization.

- Plot using Kamada-Kawai layout

  • The kk layout created a plot that was visually appealing, and highlighted potential hubs, as well as nodes on the periphery.

9. Create a plot that visualizes the average of clustering coefficients based on the degree in your network. Is the average clustering coefficient matches what the Erdos-R enyi model predicts? Include your answer and one plot in your report, but not your code or other outputs.

  • The plot that visualizes the average clustering coefficients based on the degree in my network shows that as the degree of a node increases, its clustering coefficient decreases. This is consistent with what the Erdos-Renyi model predicts. When compared against the random model, the graph has a higher average clustering coefficient, than what would be expected for a random graph.

10. Create a plot that visualizes the relationship between betweenness and degree in your network. What do you notice about this plot? Describe your observations in at most 50 words. Include your answer and the plot in your report, but not your code or other outputs.

  • The plot of the relationship between betweenness and degree in my network revealed that as the degree of a node increases, so does its betweenness centrality. This is expected as nodes with high betweenness, are often hubs, and hubs often have higher degrees.
